===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|black|lang=enm}}, {{term|blak|lang=enm}}, {{term|blake|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|blæc||black, dark", ''also'' "ink|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|blakaz|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|blakkaz||burnt|lang=gem-pro}} (compare {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|blaken|lang=nl}} 'to burn', {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|blah|lang=goh}} 'black', {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|blakkr|lang=non}} 'dark', {{term|blakra|lang=non}} 'to blink'), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|bhleg-||to burn, shine|lang=ine-pro}} (compare {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|flagare|lang=la}} 'to shine', {{term|flagrare|lang=la}} 'to burn', {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|φλόξ|tr=phlox|lang=grc|sc=Grek}} 'flame', {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|blozë||soot|lang=sq}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} ''bharga'' 'radiance'). More at [[bleach]].

